{{Campaignbox Croatian War of Independence}}
The '''1991 siege of Kijevo''' was one of the earliest conflicts in the [[Croatian War of Independence]], where the [[Yugoslav People's Army]] (JNA) led by [[Ratko Mladi<U+0107>]] and the forces of [[SAO Krajina]] under [[Milan Marti<U+0107>]] besieged the [[Croats|Croat]]-inhabited village of [[Kijevo, Croatia|Kijevo]]. The first part of the blockade took place in late April and early May 1991&mdash;lifted after negotiations in the aftermath of [[1991 protest in Split|large protests against the JNA in Split]].

The JNA renewed the blockade in mid-August. Kijevo was captured on August 26, and subsequently looted and torched. The fighting in Kijevo was significant as one of the first instances when the JNA openly sided with the SAO Krajina against Croatian authorities. The [[ethnic cleansing]] of Kijevo was later prosecuted by the [[International Criminal Tribunal for the former Yugoslavia]] and Croatian judiciary.

==Background==
{{main|Croatian War of Independence}}

In 1991, Kijevo was a village of 1,261 people, 99.6% [[Croats]], but surrounded by [[Serbs|ethnic Serbian]] villages of [[Pola<U+010D>a, <U+0160>ibenik-Knin County|Pola<U+010D>a]], [[Civljane]] and [[Cetina, Croatia|Cetina]].{{sfn|Gow|2003|p=154}}{{sfn|Silber|Little|1996|p=171}}

The ethnic Serbian villages had become part of the self-proclaimed [[SAO Krajina]] in 1990 through the so-called [[Log Revolution]]. Since August 17, 1990, Kijevo was surrounded by barricaded roads in Pola<U+010D>a and Civljane, and Kijevo's population started to organize an ad hoc militia in response to that; they smuggled weapons through mountain paths while keeping a distance from a nearby newly created outpost of the [[Yugoslav People's Army]] (JNA).{{sfn|Municipality of Kijevo|2007}}

Following the [[Plitvice Lakes incident]] of April 1, 1991, the two militias each captured several prisoners in Civljane and Kijevo.{{sfn|Municipality of Kijevo|2007}} On April 2, JNA intelligence officers reported on this, and warned how local militias in Kijevo and Civljane, otherwise separated by barricades, were engaged in armed skirmishes that threatened to escalate.{{sfn|Hrvatski vojnik|October 2012}}

==April<U+2013>May blockade==
