}}

In the night of April 27-28, a group of [[Croatian Ministry of the Interior]] officers broke through the barricades and arrived in Kijevo.{{sfn|Municipality of Kijevo|2007}} A Croatian police station was formally established in Kijevo on April 28.{{sfn|Degoricija|2008|p=49}} The JNA troops, commanded by the JNA 9th ([[Knin]]) Corps [[chief of staff]] [[Colonel]] [[Ratko Mladi<U+0107>]], moved in to enforce a blockade,{{sfn|Woodward|1995|p=142}} cutting all access and preventing delivery of supplies to Kijevo.{{sfn|Gow|2003|p=154}} The JNA subsequently entered the village in an effort to obstruct the newly created police station.{{sfn|Municipality of Kijevo|2007}} In response to the arrival of JNA tanks and APCs, the civilians in Kijevo formed a human shield to protect the police station building, starting a standoff.{{sfn|Municipality of Kijevo|2007}} On May 2, a Croatian police helicopter managed to land in Kijevo, and the blockade was strengthened in response so as to become impenetrable.{{sfn|Municipality of Kijevo|2007}}

[[Croatian President]] [[Franjo Tu<U+0111>man]] called on the public to bring the siege to its end, and the plea resulted in a [[1991 protest in Split|large-scale protest]] against the JNA in [[Split, Croatia|Split]],{{sfn|Woodward|1995|p=142}} organised by [[Croatian Trade Union Association]] in the [[Brodosplit]] Shipyard on 6 May 1991.{{sfn|Slobodna Dalmacija|6 May 2001}} The siege of Kijevo was lifted days after the protest through negotiations and two weeks after the JNA blockaded the village.{{sfn|Gow|2003|pp=154}}

==August blockade==
The May arrangement proved short-lived, as the JNA units, again led by Mladi<U+0107>, put up barricades to prevent entry into the village on August 17, 1991. The next day, Croatian Serb leader [[Milan Marti<U+0107>]] laid down an ultimatum to the police and inhabitants of Kijevo, asking them to leave the village and its vicinity within two days or face an armed attack.{{sfn|Gow|2003|pp=154-155}}{{sfn|Allcock|Milivojevi<U+0107>|Horton|1998|p=142}}

On August 23&ndash;25, Croatian forces evacuated nearly entire civilian population of the village.{{sfn|ICTY|12 June 2007|pp=61-62}} On August 25, Croatian forces launched a failed attack on JNA barracks in [[Sinj]], {{convert|38|km|abbr=off}} to the southeast of Kijevo. The objective of the attack was to obtain weapons needed as Croatian positions near Kijevo deteriorated.<ref>{{harvnb|Slobodna Dalmacija|25 August 2010}}</ref>

On August 26, the JNA attacked Kijevo, opposed by 58 policemen armed with [[small arms]] only and commanded by police station chief Martin <U+010C>i<U+010D>in <U+0160>ain. Between 05:18 and 13:00, the JNA fired 1,500 artillery shells against the village, and the [[Yugoslav Air Force]] supported the attack with 34 [[close air support]] sorties. The same afternoon, the JNA mounted a ground force assault on Kijevo.{{sfn|Novi list|27 May 2011}} The attacking force consisted of approximately 30 tanks supported by JNA infantry and Croatian Serb militia.{{sfn|Novosti|3 June 2011}}

The JNA entered the village by 16:30.{{sfn|Novi list|27 May 2011}} [[Lieutenant Colonel]] Borislav <U+0110>uki<U+0107>, in command of the Tactical Group-1 tasked with capture of Kijevo and the commanding officer of the JNA 221st Motorised Infantry Brigade, reported that the village was secured by 22:30.{{sfn|JNA|27 August 1991}} The Croatian police fled Kijevo in three groups via [[Veliki Kozjak|Mount Kozjak]] towards [[Drni<U+0161>]].{{sfn|Novi list|27 May 2011}} The remaining Croatian population left after the artillery had destroyed much of their settlements.{{sfn|Gow|2003|p=155}}{{sfn|Silber|Little|1996|pp=171<U+2013>173}} The reporter of [[Radio Television Belgrade]] Vesna Jugovi<U+0107> recorded these events. Krajina units commanded by Marti<U+0107> acted in concert with JNA to take command of the area.{{sfn|Silber|Little|1996|pp=172}}

==Aftermath==
The clash between the Croatian forces and the JNA in Kijevo was one of the first instances where the JNA openly sided with the insurgent Serbs in rapidly escalating [[Croatian War of Independence]].{{sfn|Gow|2003|pp=155}} The defending force suffered only two wounded, but one of the retreating groups was captured.{{sfn|Novi list|27 May 2011}} The group, consisting of 20 men,{{sfn|ICTY|12 June 2007|p=107}} were later released in a [[prisoner of war]] exchange.{{sfn|Novi list|27 May 2011}} The JNA suffered no casualties.{{sfn|JNA|27 August 1991}} After the JNA secured Kijevo, the village was looted and torched.{{sfn|Novosti|3 June 2011}} The destruction of Kijevo became one of the most notorious Serb crimes in the early stages of the war.{{sfn|Hoare|2010|p=122}} The JNA units which took part in the fighting in and around Kijevo advanced towards Sinj in the following few days, capturing [[Vrlika]] before being redeployed to take part in the [[Battle of <U+0160>ibenik]] in mid-September.{{sfn|Novosti|3 June 2011}}

At the [[International Criminal Tribunal for the former Yugoslavia]], the [[trial of Milan Marti<U+0107>]] resulted in a guilty verdict with regard to Marti<U+0107>'s involvement on Kijevo, and the findings of the Trial Chamber in 2007 regarding Kijevo were confirmed by the Appeals Chamber in 2008, based on witness testimonies about it being [[ethnic cleansing]].{{sfn|ICTY|12 June 2007|pp=61-62}} The events at Kijevo were not included in the indictment at the [[trial of Ratko Mladi<U+0107>]], but the Croatian judiciary tried Mladi<U+0107> [[in absentia]] for war crimes committed in Kijevo. He was convicted and sentenced to 20 years in prison.{{sfn|Jutarnji list|26 May 2011}}

